        <body>
            <div type="emblem" n="e40"><!-- Change the value of n to "e" followed by the number of the emblem. Use two digits for all numbers. -->
                <pb n="125"/><!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                
                
                <div type="title" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>
                        <lb/><orig>Embleme</orig> 40. Of the Secrets of Nature.
                        <lb/>Of two waters make one, and that will be the water of Sanctity.
                    </head>
                </div>
                
                
                <div type="epigram" xml:lang="en">
                    <head><orig>Epigramme</orig> 40.</head>
                    <lg>
                        <l>Two streaming fountains here you may behold,</l>
                        <l>One with <choice><orig>hott</orig> water, but the other cold:</l>
                        <l>That's <choice><orig>calld</orig><reg>called</reg></choice> the Boy's, but this the Virgins Spring,</l>
                        <l><orig>Joyne</orig> them, that they may be one <choice><orig>onely</orig> thing:</l>
                        <l>This river will participate of both,</l>
                        <l>As Jove (<choice><orig>Sirnamed</orig><reg>Surnamed</reg></choice>) Hammon's <choice><orig>fountaine</orig> <choice><orig>doth</orig>.</l>
                    </lg>
                </div>
                
                
                <pb n="126"/> <!-- Change to page number of the actual manuscript -->
                <div type="discourse" xml:lang="en">
                    <head>Discourse 40.</head>
                    <ab><!--Our convention will be that if we have break = "no" then it means that the word is broken across the line with a dash--> 
                        <lb/>The miracles of waters are <choice><orig>soe</orig> many and <choice><orig>soe</orig> great, as scarce to be<pc>-</pc><milestone unit="section" n="e03-01" /> <!-- Change the value of n to "e" plus the number of the emblem (in two digits), followed by a hyphen and then a two-digit count of sentence -->
                        <lb/>comprehended in a large volume, concerning which <choice><orig>severall</orig> authors<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>have here and there treated: But above all the two <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig> wa
                        <lb break="no"/>ters are celebrated with that name, because they <choice><orig>doe</orig> as it were not <choice><orig>one
                        <lb break="no"/>ly</orig> <choice><orig>æmulate</orig><reg>emulate</reg></choice>, but <choice><orig>allso</orig> exceed the virtues and <choice><orig>propertyes</orig> of all the rest.<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>The rivers Sybaris, Axus of Macedonia, and Melas of <choice><orig>Bœotia</orig><reg>Boeotia</reg></choice> make<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Cattle <choice><orig>blacke</orig>, if they <choice><orig>drinke</orig> thereof; but the rivers Crathis, Clitummus
                        <lb/>of Mevania, and Cephisus make <choice><orig>blacke</orig> Cattle white. The waters of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Sinnessa in the country of Campania takes away <choice><orig>barrennesse</orig><reg>barrenness</reg></choice> from<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>both sexes. The river Afrodisius makes women barren: Cabura a <choice><orig>foun
                        <lb break="no"/>taine</orig> of Mesopotamia <choice><orig>hath</orig> water of a sweet smell; The water of Any
                        <lb break="no"/>ger in Peloponnesus stinks very much: The <choice><orig>fountaine</orig> of Jupiter Ham
                        <lb break="no"/>mon is cold in the day time, <choice><orig>hott</orig> by night, and morning and evening<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>luke<c rend="double-hyphen">-</c>warme by <choice><orig>turnes</orig>. <choice><orig>Wee</orig> need not insist upon others, all things even
                        <lb/>contrary one to the other are <choice><orig>performd</orig> by the Philosophers waters. Of
                        <lb/>which <choice><orig>Sayth</orig> Lully in his <choice><orig>booke</orig> of the Quintessence, distin: 3. of ince
                        <lb break="no"/>ration<!-- not sure what this is -->; And <choice><orig>soe</orig> there is a twofold consideration in the act, that is, of
                        <lb/>the single nature of one <choice><orig>metall</orig> to make two contrary <choice><orig>liquours</orig> in the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>composition; one, which <choice><orig>hath</orig> a fixing, congealing, and <choice><orig>hardning</orig><reg>hardening</reg></choice> vir
                        <lb break="no"/>tue, and the other, which is volatile, unfixed, and soft. But that se
                        <lb break="no"/>cond liquor is hardened, fixed, and congealed by the first: from both<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which liquors results one stone congealed, fixed, and hardened, which
                        <lb/><orig>hath</orig> the virtue of congealing not a thing congealed, to harden a thing
                        <lb/><orig>mollifyed</orig>, and to mollify a hard thing: From which it is evident,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>what those two waters are, and why to be reduced into one water:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>For the Stone is called water, because fusible, and on the contrary,
                        <lb/>water stone, because frangible: But these waters are <choice><orig>drawne</orig> out of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>different places, sometimes in a long tract, as may be seen at Rome<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>about Aqua Virginis, and other <choice><orig>artificiall</orig> fountains, and then they<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>must be mixed by conflux, that one may be made of two. For if
                        <lb/>one be of a <choice><orig>hott</orig> and the other of a cold virtue, being mixed together
                        <lb/>they will acquire <choice><orig>mixd</orig> virtues, and after a <choice><orig>wonderfull</orig> manner re
                        <lb break="no"/>gulate one the other: From hence are most excellent <choice><orig>medicinall</orig> and
                        <lb/>bath waters to be produced, which will profligate all sorts of diseases<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>and <choice><orig>maladyes</orig>, and restore a man to <choice><orig>firme</orig> health. Nature <choice><orig>doth</orig> in
                        <lb break="no"/>deed by her occult artifice of composition confound and mix many<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>waters in the <choice><orig>bowells</orig> of the earth with <choice><orig>severall</orig> virtues of <choice><orig>Mynes</orig>, which
                        <lb/>are wholesome and <choice><orig>coḿodious</orig> to many <choice><orig>sicke</orig> and <choice><orig>infirme</orig><reg>infirm</reg></choice> persons, but
                        <lb/>if art be added with due regiment, all evacuations being <choice><orig>præmises</orig> and
                        <lb/>other things to be <choice><orig>prætermitted</orig><reg>pretermitted</reg></choice>, and mix those things that are to be<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>mixed together, that composition will be <choice><orig>farre</orig> more <choice><orig>effectuall</orig>:<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>Which, though it seem <choice><orig>artificiall</orig>, is notwithstanding merely <choice><orig>naturall</orig>,
                        <lb/>because of things different it is made one simple homogeneous matter,
                        
                        
                        
                        <pb n="127"/><fw>Discourse 40.</fw><!-- Page number of the actual manuscript, followed by the header on the page. -->
                        <lb/>which can never be effected by art: A mixtion and confusion is indeed cau
                        <lb break="no"/>sed by art, without the <choice><orig>helpe</orig> of nature <choice><orig>noe</orig> true and <choice><orig>naturall</orig> union,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>which is made by nature alone: There is an <choice><orig>artificiall</orig> mixtion of various<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>simples in Triacle, which is <choice><orig>performd</orig> by contrition and fermentation,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>but <choice><orig>noe</orig> man will (except inconsiderately) <choice><orig>affirme</orig> it to be a <choice><orig>naturall</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>composition, much <choice><orig>lesse</orig> a homogeneous medicament: As to the <choice><orig>artificiall</orig>
                        <lb/>mixtion of substances it is manifest, that they <choice><orig>doe</orig> not enter one<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>into the other in the least parts, though they cannot <choice><orig>againe</orig> be divided
                        <lb/>and separated one from the other by the industry of man. But as to
                        <lb/>the mixtion of all <choice><orig>qualityes</orig> <choice><orig>wee</orig> must enquire, whether the first Tri
                        <lb break="no"/>acles of all Simples may be reduced not one Quintessence,<del>and whol</del>
                        <lb/>or yet in their powders or substances be, as before, as accidents in a subject,
                        <lb/>or <choice><orig>colour</orig> in a wall; and then what is to be <choice><orig>sayd</orig> of the second, third, and
                        <lb/>fourth <choice><orig>qualityes</orig>? Probable it is that all the <choice><orig>qualityes</orig> are yet <choice><orig>inhærent</orig><reg>inherent</reg></choice>
                        <lb/>in their <choice><orig>owne</orig> subjects, and not compounded together by a true <choice><orig>natu
                        <lb break="no"/>rall</orig> mixtion; otherwise, if the <choice><orig>qualityes</orig> should relinquish their <choice><orig>bo
                        <lb/>dyes</orig>, there would be four Quintessences in every <seg rend="superscript">2</seg> composition <seg rend="superscript">1</seg> <choice><orig>arti
                        <lb break="no"/>ficiall</orig>, according to the number of the order of the <choice><orig>qualityes</orig>, first,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>second Ct. without their <choice><orig>bodyes</orig>, and separable; which they say
                        <lb/>is not <choice><orig>soe</orig> with the coagulum of a hare, which being in flux<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>by the tenuity of the blood stops and as it were coagulates it,<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>but in the coagulation and concretion <choice><orig>cutts</orig><reg>cuts</reg></choice> and resolves the same;
                        <lb/>soe the operations of vinegar, lead, and many other things are con
                        <lb break="no"/>trary according to the different use of them, because nature <choice><orig>hath</orig><pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>soe wonderfully mixed them: <choice><orig>Soe</orig> <choice><orig>allso</orig> <choice><orig>hath</orig> the <choice><orig>Philosophicall</orig>
                        <lb/>water different and contrary virtues, because nature <choice><orig>hath</orig> by the<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/><orig>helpe</orig> of art mixed it with things contrary into one indivisible<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>substance, which is nothing <choice><orig>els</orig> but a Quintessence, in respect of<pc>-</pc>
                        <lb/>other things to be mixed with it<pc>. . . . . . .</pc>
                    </ab>   
                </div>
                
            </div>
